<eml:eml xmlns:eml="eml://ecoinformatics.org/eml-2.1.1" xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="eml://ecoinformatics.org/eml-2.1.1 http://rs.gbif.org/schema/eml-gbif-profile/1.0.1/eml.xsd" packageId="e7e5401d-cb2f-411a-b94f-8b6cee64dc83" system="https://symbiota.org" scope="system" xml:lang="eng"><dataset><title xml:lang="eng">Ecdysis general data extract</title><creator id="b925ff4c-8eba-495c-b5ed-852c7affb2ea"><organizationName>Ecdysis</organizationName><electronicMailAddress></electronicMailAddress><onlineUrl>https://ecdysis.org/index.php</onlineUrl></creator><metadataProvider><organizationName>Ecdysis</organizationName><electronicMailAddress></electronicMailAddress><onlineUrl>https://ecdysis.org/index.php</onlineUrl></metadataProvider><pubDate>2026-06-19</pubDate><language>eng</language><associatedParty><individualName><surName>Zhu</surName><givenName>Vivian</givenName></individualName><electronicMailAddress>hzhu22@alumni.nd.edu</electronicMailAddress><role>datasetOriginator</role></associatedParty></dataset><additionalMetadata><metadata><symbiota id="b925ff4c-8eba-495c-b5ed-852c7affb2ea"><dateStamp>2026-06-19T08:44:36-07:00</dateStamp><citation identifier="d18d14ed-737a-4fa8-b9e3-28d52bab0244">Ecdysis - d18d14ed-737a-4fa8-b9e3-28d52bab0244</citation><physical><characterEncoding>UTF-8</characterEncoding><dataFormat><externallyDefinedFormat><formatName>Darwin Core Archive</formatName></externallyDefinedFormat></dataFormat></physical><collection identifier="875b3050-dc20-414e-a67b-eb81b0f3fc2d" id="62"><alternateIdentifier>https://ecdysis.org/collections/misc/collprofiles.php?collid=62</alternateIdentifier><parentCollectionIdentifier>NAU</parentCollectionIdentifier><collectionIdentifier>NAAC</collectionIdentifier><collectionName>Northern Arizona University - Arthropod Collection</collectionName><resourceLogoUrl>https://ecdysis.org/content/collicon/nau-agfr.jpg</resourceLogoUrl><onlineUrl></onlineUrl><intellectualRights>http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/</intellectualRights><additionalInfo>Northern Arizona University - Arthropod Collection (NAU-NAU)</additionalInfo><associatedParty><individualName><surName>Gustafson</surName><givenName>Grey</givenName></individualName><positionName>Curator</positionName><electronicMailAddress>grey.gustafson@nau.edu</electronicMailAddress><userId>https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2014-7128</userId></associatedParty><associatedParty><individualName><surName>Alpert</surName><givenName>Gary</givenName></individualName><positionName>Project manager</positionName><electronicMailAddress>garydalpert@gmail.com</electronicMailAddress></associatedParty><associatedParty><individualName><surName>Holditch</surName><givenName>Zane</givenName></individualName><positionName>Project manager</positionName><electronicMailAddress>zh57@nau.edu</electronicMailAddress></associatedParty><abstract><para>&lt;p&gt;The Northern Arizona University - Arthropod Collection (NAAC), previously the Colorado Plateau Museum of Arthropod Biodiversity (CPMAB), houses over 250,000 arthropod specimens, primarily from the southwestern United States and Mexico. Specimens are being added each year, primarily from Military Reservations, National Parks and Monuments, The Nature Conservancy, and a network of common gardens managed by the Southwest Experimental Garden Array (SEGA). Many specimen occurrence data are combined with high resolution images.&lt;/p&gt;</para></abstract></collection><collection identifier="e1858cf7-d4c7-4eb9-b174-597ffb8d8f2b" id="158"><alternateIdentifier>https://ecdysis.org/collections/misc/collprofiles.php?collid=158</alternateIdentifier><parentCollectionIdentifier>CSU</parentCollectionIdentifier><collectionIdentifier>CSUC</collectionIdentifier><collectionName>C.P. Gillette Museum of Arthropod Diversity</collectionName><resourceLogoUrl>https://ecdysis.org/content/collicon/csucsuc.jpg</resourceLogoUrl><onlineUrl>https://agbio.agsci.colostate.edu/gillette-museum</onlineUrl><intellectualRights>https://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/</intellectualRights><additionalInfo>Department of Bioagricultural Sciences</additionalInfo><associatedParty><individualName><surName>Harp</surName><givenName>Chuck</givenName></individualName><electronicMailAddress>Chuck.Harp@colostate.edu</electronicMailAddress></associatedParty><abstract><para>&lt;p&gt;The collection houses approximately 5 million specimens representing about 60,000 species with fifty primary types and 1,000 secondary types. More than 10,000 specimens are added to the collection each year. As a large and comprehensive holding of arthropods, predominately insects, in the Southern Rocky Mountains, it is a major resource for regional and national biodiversity investigations. Much of the material has been identified by specialists to the specific level. Examples of the unique quality of material include the aphids, other Homoptera, Coleoptera, Diptera, Hymenoptera, Lepidoptera, and all aquatic orders. It serves as the repository for arthropod inventories of over thirty National Parks including Canyonlands, Guadalupe Mountains, Yellowstone, Glacier, Carlsbad Caverns, Great Sand Dunes, Mesa Verde, Rocky Mountain, Dinosaur, and Yucca House and Colorado National Monuments.&lt;/p&gt;</para></abstract></collection></symbiota></metadata></additionalMetadata></eml:eml>
